A.5 Proof of Imported Theorem 4.6 (Kuramoto Synchronization)

Theorem 4.6 (Kuramoto Synchronization).
For a population of identical oscillators (\omega_i=\omega), the fully synchronized state \theta_i=\theta is stable for any K>0. For heterogeneous frequencies drawn from a unimodal symmetric distribution g(\omega), there exists a critical coupling K_c = 2/(\pi g(0)) such that for K>K_c the incoherent state loses stability and a partially synchronized state emerges with order parameter r = \sqrt{1 - K_c/K}.

Proof sketch.
The Kuramoto model is \dot{\theta}_i = \omega_i + \frac{K}{N}\sum_{j=1}^N \sin(\theta_j-\theta_i). Define the order parameter r e^{i\psi} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_j e^{i\theta_j}. The dynamics reduce to \dot{\theta}_i = \omega_i + K r \sin(\psi-\theta_i). For identical oscillators, a transformation to rotating frame shows that the fully synchronized state is stable. For heterogeneous oscillators, the Ott–Antonsen ansatz (2008) reduces the system to a low‑dimensional equation for the order parameter. The linear stability analysis of the incoherent state yields the critical coupling K_c = 2/(\pi g(0)). For K>K_c, a stable synchronized branch appears with the given expression for r. ∎

Note. Full derivation can be found in Strogatz (2000), Acebrón et al. (2005).

