A.6 Proof of Proposition 4.4 (Inaccessibility After Fold Bifurcation)

Proposition 4.4.
In a fold bifurcation, the prior attractor becomes inaccessible after \mu>\mu_c; restoration is impossible.

Proof.
The normal form of a fold (saddle‑node) bifurcation is \dot{x} = \mu + x^2. For \mu<0, there are two equilibria: x = \pm\sqrt{-\mu}, one stable, one unstable. At \mu=0, they coalesce and disappear. For \mu>0, there are no real equilibria; all trajectories go to infinity. Since the prior attractor corresponded to the stable equilibrium that no longer exists, there is no state to which the system can return that would constitute restoration. ∎

