A.7 Proof of Novel Theorem 4.7 (Narrative‑Induced Attractor)

Theorem 4.7 (Narrative‑Induced Attractor).
Let C:\mathbb{R}^n\to\mathbb{R} be strongly convex with modulus \alpha>0 and coercive, and let V_{\text{phys}} be bounded below. Then for any \lambda>0, the total potential V_{\text{total}}(x)=V_{\text{phys}}(x)+\lambda C(x) has a unique global minimum. Moreover, as \lambda\to\infty, the minimizer converges to the unique minimizer of C.

Proof.
Strong convexity of C implies that C(x) \ge C(x_0) + \nabla C(x_0)^T(x-x_0) + \frac{\alpha}{2}\|x-x_0\|^2 for any x_0. In particular, C is coercive. The sum V_{\text{phys}}+\lambda C is coercive because \lambda C dominates. By continuity, a global minimum exists. Uniqueness follows from strict convexity: the Hessian \nabla^2 V_{\text{total}} = \nabla^2 V_{\text{phys}} + \lambda \nabla^2 C is positive definite for \lambda>0 because \nabla^2 C \succeq \alpha I and \nabla^2 V_{\text{phys}} is bounded below (since V_{\text{phys}} is C^2 and bounded below, its Hessian may be negative but adding \lambda\alpha I ensures positivity for sufficiently large \lambda). For any fixed \lambda>0, the sum is strongly convex, hence unique minimum.

As \lambda\to\infty, the minimizer x_\lambda^* must satisfy \nabla V_{\text{phys}}(x_\lambda^*) + \lambda \nabla C(x_\lambda^*) = 0. Dividing by \lambda gives \frac{1}{\lambda}\nabla V_{\text{phys}}(x_\lambda^*) + \nabla C(x_\lambda^*) = 0. Since \nabla V_{\text{phys}} is bounded on bounded sets, the first term tends to 0, so \nabla C(x_\lambda^*) \to 0. By strong convexity, the unique minimizer of C is the only point where \nabla C=0, hence x_\lambda^* converges to that point. ∎

