A.8 Proof of Novel Proposition 4.8 (Collapse Diagnostics)

Proposition 4.8 (Collapse Diagnostics).
In a stochastic gradient system approaching a fold bifurcation, the AR(1) coefficient and variance diverge.

Proof.
Consider the linearized SDE around a stable equilibrium: d\delta = -A\delta\,dt + \sigma dW, with A symmetric positive definite. The stationary solution is an Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process. Its covariance matrix satisfies A\Sigma + \Sigma A = \sigma^2 I, so \Sigma = \frac{\sigma^2}{2} A^{-1}. The discrete‑time sample at intervals \Delta t gives an AR(1) process with coefficient \rho = e^{-A\Delta t}. For a scalar approximation, if \lambda_{\max} is the smallest eigenvalue of A (the slowest decay rate), then the autocorrelation at lag 1 is approximately e^{-\lambda_{\max}\Delta t}, and the variance is approximately \frac{\sigma^2}{2\lambda_{\max}}. As the bifurcation approaches, \lambda_{\max}\to 0^+, so \rho\to 1 and \text{Var}\to\infty. ∎

