A.9 Proof of Lemma 4.9.1 (Maakoul’s Lemma – Non‑Coercive Extension)

Lemma 4.9.1 (Maakoul’s Lemma – Non‑Coercive Extension).
Assume V_{\text{phys}} is C^2, bounded below, and its Hessian is bounded below by m\in\mathbb{R} (i.e., \nabla^2 V_{\text{phys}}(x) \succeq m I for all x). Let C be strongly convex with modulus \alpha>0 and coercive. Then for any \gamma, \lambda >0 such that \gamma + \lambda\alpha > |m|, the potential V_{\text{total}}(x) = V_{\text{phys}}(x) + \frac{\gamma}{2}\|x\|^2 + \lambda C(x) is strongly convex and coercive, hence has a unique global minimizer. The gradient flow converges globally to this minimizer.

Proof.
Coercivity: The term \frac{\gamma}{2}\|x\|^2 + \lambda C(x) is coercive because it grows at least quadratically (since C is coercive). Adding a bounded‑below function preserves coercivity.

Strong convexity: Compute Hessian: \nabla^2 V_{\text{total}} = \nabla^2 V_{\text{phys}} + \gamma I + \lambda \nabla^2 C. Since \nabla^2 V_{\text{phys}} \succeq m I and \nabla^2 C \succeq \alpha I, we have

\nabla^2 V_{\text{total}} \succeq (m + \gamma + \lambda\alpha) I.
\]  

The condition \gamma + \lambda\alpha > |m| ensures m + \gamma + \lambda\alpha > 0. Therefore \nabla^2 V_{\text{total}} \succeq \delta I with \delta = m + \gamma + \lambda\alpha > 0, i.e., V_{\text{total}} is strongly convex. A strongly convex coercive function has a unique global minimizer, and the gradient flow converges to it from any initial condition with exponential rate \delta. ∎

