A.10 Proof of Novel Theorem 5.1 (Existence of New Attractor within Desirable Region)

Theorem 5.1 (Existence of New Attractor within Desirable Region).
Let A be positive definite, W bounded below and coercive on D, and C strongly convex and coercive. Then V'(x) = \frac12 (x-P_D x)^T A (x-P_D x) + W(x) + \lambda C(x) has a unique global minimum. Moreover, for any \varepsilon>0, there exists \lambda_0 such that for \lambda>\lambda_0, the minimizer satisfies C(x^*) \le \min C + \varepsilon.

Proof.
Uniqueness follows from strong convexity of the quadratic term and C, and coercivity of W ensures the sum is coercive. The location of the minimum: let x_\lambda^* be the minimizer. Then \nabla W(x_\lambda^*) + A(x_\lambda^*-P_D x_\lambda^*) + \lambda \nabla C(x_\lambda^*) = 0 (taking into account projection). As \lambda\to\infty, \nabla C(x_\lambda^*) \to 0, so x_\lambda^* tends to the minimizer of C (since C is strongly convex). Thus for large \lambda, C(x_\lambda^*) is arbitrarily close to \min C. ∎

