A.11 Proof of Novel Theorem 5.2 (Stabilization by Damping)

Theorem 5.2 (Stabilization by Damping).
Let x_0 be a local minimum of V'. For \gamma > \max_i |\lambda_i(\nabla^2 V'(x_0))|, the linearization of \dot{x} = -\nabla V'(x) - \gamma x around x_0 has all eigenvalues with negative real part, making x_0 locally asymptotically stable.

Proof.
The Jacobian of the augmented system is J = -\nabla^2 V'(x_0) - \gamma I. Let \lambda_i be eigenvalues of \nabla^2 V'(x_0). The eigenvalues of J are -\lambda_i - \gamma. If \gamma > |\lambda_i| for all i, then \text{Re}(-\lambda_i - \gamma) < 0. Hence J is Hurwitz, and the equilibrium is asymptotically stable. ∎

