A.12 Proof of Convergence for Debris Mapping (Section 5.1.2)

Proposition (Convergence of Subspace Estimation).
Let y_t be the observed state. Let \hat{D}_k be the estimated subspace at iteration k, and P_k the orthogonal projection onto \hat{D}_k. Define the innovation error \nu_k = y_{\text{obs}} - P_k y_{\text{obs}} and cost J(P) = \mathbb{E}[\|\nu_k\|^2]. Using stochastic gradient descent on the Grassmann manifold P_{k+1} = P_k - \eta \nabla_P J(P_k), the sequence P_k converges to the projection P^* onto the true slow manifold D^*.

Proof.
The true slow manifold is the subspace that minimizes the variance of the residual after projection, i.e., D^* = \arg\min_{D} \mathbb{E}[\|y - P_D y\|^2]. The cost function J(P) is a convex quadratic form on the Grassmannian because it is the trace of (I-P)\Sigma_y(I-P) with \Sigma_y the covariance of y. Convexity on the Grassmannian follows from the fact that the set of projection matrices is convex in the ambient space and the function is quadratic. Stochastic gradient descent with a sufficiently small learning rate \eta converges to the global minimum under standard conditions (bounded gradients, convexity). The gradient on the Grassmann manifold can be computed explicitly; the update corresponds to a form of online PCA. Convergence results for such algorithms are well‑established (see e.g., Warmuth & Kuzmin, 2008). Hence P_k \to P^*. ∎

