A.13 Derivation of Kramers’ Escape Time for Agency (Section 4.6.1)

Proposition (Agency as Symmetry Breaking).
Consider a post‑collapse potential with multiple local minima \{x^*_1, x^*_2, \dots, x^*_n\}. Introduce a narrative penalty \lambda C(x, A_t) where A_t selects a target minimum x^*_2 (i.e., \arg\min C = x^*_2). The mean escape time from the basin of x^*_2 to another minimum is

\tau \approx \exp\!\left(\frac{2\lambda \Delta C}{\sigma^2}\right),
\]  

where \Delta C is the barrier height of C relative to other minima. As \lambda\to\infty, the escape time diverges, locking the system into the chosen attractor.

Proof.
Kramers’ escape theory (Freidlin & Wentzell, 2012) gives the mean first passage time from a well to a saddle in a gradient system with small noise \sigma:

\tau \approx \frac{2\pi}{\sqrt{|V''(x_0)|V''(x^*)}} \exp\!\left(\frac{2\Delta V}{\sigma^2}\right),
\]  

where \Delta V is the potential barrier from the starting well to the saddle. Here the total potential is V_{\text{total}} = V_{\text{phys}} + \lambda C. The barrier from x^*_2 to an adjacent saddle x_s is \Delta V_{\text{total}} = \Delta V_{\text{phys}} + \lambda \Delta C, where \Delta C = C(x_s)-C(x^*_2) > 0. Substituting into the exponential factor gives

\tau \approx \exp\!\left(\frac{2(\Delta V_{\text{phys}} + \lambda \Delta C)}{\sigma^2}\right) = e^{2\Delta V_{\text{phys}}/\sigma^2} \cdot e^{2\lambda \Delta C/\sigma^2}.
\]  

As \lambda\to\infty, the exponential dominates, so \tau \to \infty. Thus the system remains in the chosen attractor with probability 1. ∎

