A.14 Thermodynamic Justification of the Pulsar Analogy (Section 1.2.1)

Proposition (Thermodynamic Necessity of the Second Orbit).
The reorganization of debris into a planetary system after a supernova is a thermodynamic necessity to maximize entropy production and reach a new steady state.

Proof.
Let S be the entropy of the system. The supernova event releases a large amount of free energy, causing a massive entropy production \Delta S_{\text{collapse}} \gg 0. The system is driven far from equilibrium. According to the Maximum Entropy Production Principle (MEPP) and Prigogine’s theory of dissipative structures (Prigogine, 1977), such systems self‑organize into structures that maximize the rate of entropy production in order to dissipate the available free energy as quickly as possible. A random cloud of gas has a low entropy production rate; a gravitationally bound planetary system orbiting a pulsar has a much higher rate because it channels the pulsar’s radiation into structured motion and heat. Therefore, the formation of the “Second Orbit” is not accidental but is a necessary outcome of non‑equilibrium thermodynamics under the new constraints. ∎

