Appendix D: Glossary of Terms

· Attractor: A set of states toward which a system tends to evolve, often a local minimum of a potential function.
· Bifurcation: A qualitative change in the structure of a dynamical system as a parameter varies.
· Coercive function: A function f(x) such that f(x) \to +\infty as \|x\|\to\infty.
· Collapse: An irreversible phase transition in which the prior attractor landscape is destroyed.
· Debris Mapping: The iterative identification of surviving state variables (the “debris”) after collapse.
· Fold bifurcation (saddle‑node): A bifurcation where two equilibria coalesce and disappear, rendering the prior attractor inaccessible.
· Gradient system: A dynamical system \dot{x} = -\nabla V(x) that follows the steepest descent of a potential.
· Kramers’ escape time: The mean first passage time for a stochastic system to leave a potential well.
· Kuramoto model: A model for synchronization of coupled oscillators.
· Maakoul’s Theorem: The theorem stating that damping and narrative penalty together create a unique global attractor even when the physical potential is non‑coercive.
· Narrative penalty: A convex, coercive function added to the potential to encode meaning constraints.
· Restoration Fallacy: The mistaken belief that a collapsed system can return to its pre‑collapse state.
· Second Orbit: A new stable configuration that emerges from the debris of collapse under new constraints.
· Strong convexity: A function f is strongly convex with modulus \alpha if \nabla^2 f \succeq \alpha I.

